Ecological Niche Models

Model fitting

Model fitting is the heart of any SDM application. Many different algorithms are available to fit the relationship between occurrence records and environmental predictors.

Generalised linear models

Generalised linear model (GLM) is a typical parametric regression algorithm that can fit linear, quadratic or higher polynomial terms and interactions between predictors.

# load a vector defining global landmasses and crop to the Iberia Peninsula extent
world <- ne_countries(scale = "medium")
IberianExtent <- extent(-15, 5, 25, 46)
iberianLandMass <- crop(world, IberianExtent)

# read presence / absence datasets for an intertidal species
absences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Kelp-monitoring-absent.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Kelp-monitoring-presence.csv", sep = ";")

    geom_point(data = presences, aes(Lon, Lat), color = "#BA323F")

# get environmental conditions
envConditions <- load_layers(c("BO2_tempmax_ss", "BO2_nitratemean_ss"))

# mask rasters to coastline regions (intertidal species) and crop to the region of interest
coastline <- raster("Data/rasterLayers/CoastLine.tif")
envConditions <- mask(envConditions, coastline)
envConditions <- crop(envConditions, IberianExtent)
plot(envConditions)

# extract environmental values and make an object with all information to model
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, absences, envConditions)

# fit a binomial GLM to the dataset
model <- trainGLM(modelData)

# predict the distribution with the GLM over a raster stack
map <- predict(envConditions, model, type = "response")

# transform to a data.frame for ggplot to read
map <- as.data.frame(map, xy = T, na.rm = T)

    scale_fill_gradient(low = "#3296BA", high = "#BA323F") + labs(fill = "Probability")

Pseudo-absence data

If true absence data is not available, but one wants to fit an ecological niche model, pseudo-absence data can be generated.

# generate pseudo-absences
pAbsences <- pseudoAbsences(envConditions, presences, n = 100)

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

Maximum Entropy

Maxent only uses presence data and the algorithm compares the locations of where a species has been found to all the environments that are available in the study region.

# load a presence dataset for a deep coral
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# load layers of temperatures, oxygen and productivity
envConditions <- load_layers(c("BO2_tempmin_bdmean", "BO2_tempmax_bdmean", "BO2_dissoxmean_bdmean", 
    "BO2_ppmean_bdmean"))

# crop layers to the European extent
europeanExtent <- extent(-15, 40, 25, 50)
envConditions <- crop(envConditions, europeanExtent)
S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot environmental layers
plot(envConditions)

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# generate background information
background <- backgroundInformation(envConditions, n = 10000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, background, envConditions)

# fit a Maxent model to the dataset
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData)

# predict with Maxent to raster stack
map <- predict(model, envConditions, type = "logistic")
S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot prediction of suitable habitats
plot(map, col = brewer.pal(n = 11, name = "YlOrRd"), main = "Suitable habitats for the coral P. clavata")

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

Model transferability

Model transferability is the process of transferring a model to a new dataset.

Temporal transferability

Temporal transferability is the task of predicting to a distinct time than where the model was trained.

# load a presence dataset for deep coral
presences <- read.csv("Data/dataBases/Paramuricea_clavata.csv", sep = ";")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# load layers of sea surface temperatures
envlCondPresent <- load_layers(c("BO2_tempmin_bdmean", "BO2_tempmax_bdmean"))
envCondRCP26 <- load_layers(c("BO2_RCP26_2100_tempmin_bdmean", "BO2_RCP26_2100_tempmax_bdmean"))
S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

Predictor layers must have the same name for proper transferability.

# compare layer names
names(envlCondPresent)
## [1] "BO2_tempmin_bdmean" "BO2_tempmax_bdmean"
names(envCondRCP26)
## [1] "BO2_RCP26_2100_tempmin_bdmean" "BO2_RCP26_2100_tempmax_bdmean"
# change layer names for them to match
names(envCondRCP26) <- c("BO2_tempmin_bdmean", "BO2_tempmax_bdmean")

# crop layers to the European extent
europeanExtent <- extent(-15, 40, 25, 50)
envlCondPresent <- crop(envlCondPresent, europeanExtent)
envCondRCP26 <- crop(envCondRCP26, europeanExtent)
S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# generate background information
background <- backgroundInformation(envlCondPresent, n = 10000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, background, envlCondPresent)

# fit a Maxent model to the dataset
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, folds = NULL)

# predict with Maxent to the different time periods
map <- predict(model, envlCondPresent, type = c("logistic"))
mapRCP26 <- predict(model, envCondRCP26, type = c("logistic"))
S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot prediction
plot(map, main = "Predicted distribution of P.clavata for the Present", col = brewer.pal(n = 11, 
    name = "YlOrRd"))

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot projection
plot(mapRCP26, main = "Predicted distribution of P.clavata for the Future (RCP26)", col = brewer.pal(n = 11, 
    name = "YlOrRd"))

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot difference in habitat suitability
differenceRCP26 <- mapRCP26 - map
plot(differenceRCP26, main = "Difference in habitat suitablity (RCP26)", col = brewer.pal(n = 11, 
    name = "RdBu"))

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

Spatial transferability

Spatial transferability is the task of predicting to a distinct region than where the model was trained.

# load a presence dataset for an invasive species
presences <- getOccurrencesGBIF("Undaria pinnatifida")
presences <- presences[, c("Lon", "Lat")]

# load layers of light, sea surface temperatures and nutrients
envConditions <- load_layers(c("BO2_lightbotmean_bdmean", "BO2_tempmin_bdmean", "BO2_tempmax_bdmean", 
    "BO2_nitratemean_bdmean"))

# crop layers to the native extent
nativeExtent <- extent(115, 155, 20, 50)
envConditionsNative <- crop(envConditions, nativeExtent)

# crop layers to the Invasive European extent
europeanExtent <- extent(-15, 40, 25, 75)
envConditionsEurope <- crop(envConditions, europeanExtent)
S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# Plot environmental conditions of the native range
plot(envConditionsNative)

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# Plot environmental conditions of the invasive range
plot(envConditionsEurope)

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# generate background information
background <- backgroundInformation(envConditionsNative, n = 10000)

# extract environmental values and make a data.frame with PA information
modelData <- prepareModelData(presences, background, envConditionsNative)

# fit a Maxent model to the dataset
model <- train("Maxnet", modelData, folds = NULL)

# predict with Maxent to the different regions
mapNative <- predict(model, envConditionsNative, type = c("logistic"))
mapEurope <- predict(model, envConditionsEurope, type = c("logistic"))
S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot suitable habitats for native extent
plot(mapNative, main = "Native suitable habitats of Undaria pinnatifida", col = brewer.pal(n = 11, 
    name = "YlOrRd"))

S6 : Developing Ecological Niche Models

# plot suitable habitats for invasive extent
plot(mapEurope, main = "Invasive suitable habitats of Undaria pinnatifida", col = brewer.pal(n = 11, 
    name = "YlOrRd"))
